{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 09:35:24.406423", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Codes: K - kernel route, C - connected, S - static, R - RIP,\\n       O - OSPF, I - IS-IS, B - BGP, E - EIGRP, N - NHRP,\\n       T - Table, v - VNC, V - VNC-Direct, A - Babel, F - PBR,\\n       f - OpenFabric,\\n       > - selected route, * - FIB route, q - queued, r - rejected, b - backup\\n       t - trapped, o - offload failure\\n\\nO>* 10.1.1.0/24 [110/40] via 172.16.0.10, eth5, weight 1, 00:00:05\\nO>* 10.2.1.0/24 [110/40] via 172.16.0.10, eth5, weight 1, 00:00:08\\nO   10.200.0.0/24 [110/10] is directly connected, br0, weight 1, 00:00:58\\nC>* 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected, br0, 00:00:58\\nO>* 172.16.0.0/31 [110/30] via 172.16.0.10, eth5, weight 1, 00:00:08\\nO>* 172.16.0.2/31 [110/20] via 172.16.0.10, eth5, weight 1, 00:00:08\\nO>* 172.16.0.4/31 [110/20] via 172.16.0.10, eth5, weight 1, 00:00:08\\nO>* 172.16.0.6/31 [110/30] via 172.16.0.10, eth5, weight 1, 00:00:08\\nO>* 172.16.0.8/31 [110/30] via 172.16.0.10, eth5, weight 1, 00:00:08\\nO   172.16.0.10/31 [110/10] is directly connected, eth5, weight 1, 00:00:58\\nC>* 172.16.0.10/31 is directly connected, eth5, 00:00:58' name='frr_show_ip_route' id='711daae8-28fa-4b8c-8384-c8b53fcc1659' tool_call_id='call_9wkcuMQNqdB9e3q2NnGMvSmw'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 09:36:47.793701", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report\nObjective\n- Assess the current health of the lab network (FRR OSPF multi-area hierarchical design).\n- Detect any abnormal behavior.\n- Localize any faulty devices or links and identify root cause(s) where present.\n\nSummary / high-level conclusion\n- The network is converged and operational. End-to-end IP reachability between access hosts (host_1_1_1_1, host_2_1_1_1), the DNS server (10.200.0.2) and the web servers (10.200.0.3–.6) was verified by active tests. No packet loss was observed in the targeted ping tests and OSPF-learned routes for all user subnets and the server subnet are present on the core and distribution devices.\n- I did not find any critical fault (down interfaces, routing blackholes, OSPF adjacency failures or packet loss) in the data collected. There are a couple of minor observations worth noting (see \"Non-fatal observations\").\n\nWhat I ran / data examined\n- Global reachability sweep (summary).\n- Per-host network configuration (ifconfig / ip addr / ip route) for:\n  - Hosts: host_1_1_1_1, host_2_1_1_1\n  - Servers: dns_server, web_server_0..web_server_3\n  - Core routers: router_core_1, router_core_2, router_core_3\n  - Distribution/server-access switches: switch_dist_1_1, switch_dist_2_1, switch_server_access\n- Targeted ping tests:\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> dns_server (10.200.0.2)\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> dns_server\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> host_2_1_1_1\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> web_server_0\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> web_server_0\n- OSPF routing table (show ip route via FRR) from all core routers and the server-access router.\n\nConcrete test results (representative)\n- host_1_1_1_1 -> 10.200.0.2 : 4/4 replies, avg RTT ~3.6 ms, 0% loss\n- host_2_1_1_1 -> 10.200.0.2 : 4/4 replies, avg RTT ~4.0 ms, 0% loss\n- host_1_1_1_1 -> host_2_1_1_1 : 4/4 replies, avg RTT ~4.7 ms, 0% loss\n- host_1_1_1_1 -> web_server_0 : 4/4 replies, avg RTT ≈ 5–7 ms (some variance between runs), 0% loss\n- web_server_0..3 -> dns_server : ICMP reachable (small RTTs, 0% loss)\n- All relevant device interfaces reported UP and RUNNING; no rx/tx errors reported in ifconfig outputs.\n- OSPF-derived routes for:\n  - 10.1.1.0/24 (access network 1), 10.2.1.0/24 (access network 2) and 10.200.0.0/24 (server farm) appear in the cores' routing tables with next-hops that correspond to expected /31 links.\n\nDevice/localization status (devices checked and state)\n- router_core_1: interfaces UP; OSPF routes present (learns/advertises 10.1.1.0, 10.2.1.0, 10.200.0.0). ip route entries show expected next-hops.\n- router_core_2: interfaces UP; OSPF routes present and consistent with topology.\n- router_core_3: interfaces UP; OSPF routes present.\n- switch_dist_1_1 (distribution for core1/topology): br0 = 10.1.1.1, eth0 = 172.16.0.7; interface up; OSPF routes present.\n- switch_dist_2_1: br0 = 10.2.1.1, eth0 = 172.16.0.9; interface up; OSPF routes present.\n- switch_server_access: br0 = 10.200.0.1, eth5 = 172.16.0.11; interfaces up; server subnet connected; OSPF routes present.\n- Hosts:\n  - host_1_1_1_1: 10.1.1.2/24 default gw 10.1.1.1; interface UP; ICMP OK.\n  - host_2_1_1_1: 10.2.1.218/24 default gw 10.2.1.1; interface UP; ICMP OK.\n- DNS server: 10.200.0.2 default gw 10.200.0.1; reachable.\n- web_server_0..3: 10.200.0.3–.6 default gw 10.200.0.1; reachable.\n\nAnomalies / non-fatal observations\n- Initial automated reachability sweep returned many \"unknown\" entries for certain src-dst pairs (this was a high-level sweep, not all hosts were tested in that pass). Subsequent targeted pings confirmed reachability. The \"unknown\" entries appear to be the result of partial/limited sweep and not an indication of connectivity problems for the endpoints I retested.\n- OSPF path cost asymmetry across devices:\n  - Some routers show different OSPF metrics (e.g., the server-access switch shows higher cost values for certain external networks vs. the core routers). This is consistent with the network topology and multiple links; it results in different preferred next-hops on some devices. It is not an operational failure but is visible in the routing tables.\n- Use of .0 IPs in /31 subnets:\n  - Some core interfaces are assigned addresses ending in .0 (e.g., router_core_1 eth0 = 172.16.0.0/31). While RFC 3021 (/31) allows using both addresses, using a network/base address that looks like a traditional \"network\" address can be surprising to operators who expect conventional .0/.1 usage. This is a configuration detail—functional here but noteworthy.\n- Small RTT variance to web_server_0:\n  - One run from host_1 to web_server_0 showed an elevated single-sample RTT (~15.9 ms) while other samples were lower; all samples still arrived (0% loss). This looks like transient jitter on that path rather than persistent loss.\n\nRoot-cause / fault localization\n- No fault / outage detected. All devices and links that I inspected are up and forwarding. OSPF is exchanging routes and the routing tables show expected learned routes for user and server subnets.\n- Where minor oddities exist (unknowns from an initial sweep, metric asymmetry, occasional single-sample RTT spike) they are either operational/expected (OSPF metrics vary by path length/cost) or transient jitter that does not indicate a failed device.\n\nConfidence and recommended follow-up (diagnostic only)\n- Confidence in the \"network healthy\" assessment: high, based on:\n  - All checked interfaces are UP.\n  - No RX/TX errors shown on interfaces.\n  - OSPF route presence and expected next-hops on core + distribution + server-access devices.\n  - Zero packet loss on ICMP tests between access hosts, DNS and web servers.\n- If further verification is desired (optional, diagnostic-only):\n  - Run continuous ping or MTR between problematic/observed jitter endpoints to check for intermittent latency spikes.\n  - Snapshots of FRR OSPF neighbor/adjacency state (vtysh show ip ospf neighbo